# Identifiers and naming (strict)

- **Never use Turkish words in code identifiers**: variables, parameters, functions, methods, struct/enum fields, type aliases, modules, and file names that encode API (e.g. `user_status`, not `kullanici_durumu`).
- **Rust**: `snake_case` for functions, locals, modules; `UpperCamelCase` for types; constants `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE`. Follow the idioms in [Rust API guidelines](https://rust-lang.github.io/api-guidelines/).
- **TypeScript/React**: `camelCase` for variables and functions; `PascalCase` for components and types; avoid Hungarian notation unless already project-standard.
- **Wire format vs code**: If a JSON/API field must stay Turkish for backward compatibility, keep the **Rust/TS identifier in English** and map with `#[serde(rename = "...")]` / explicit DTO mapping — do not encode Turkish in the symbol name used in logic.

When touching legacy Turkish-named fields, prefer incremental migration (English in code + serde rename) rather than adding new Turkish identifiers.

- **Log messages:** Prefer **English** for new operator-facing log text when practical (searchability, SIEM). Use **`trace` / `debug` / `info` / `warn` / `error` / `critical`** per `docs/QTSS_MASTER_DEV_GUIDE.md` §8.1 (`qtss_common::log_critical` for critical). Structured field names stay English (`qtss_module`, `is_critical`).
